[size=18pt][b]Computica's Faction Forks[/b][/size]
[i]Restoring abandoned factions • Translating Chinese mods • Cleaning code • Bridging compatibility • Polishing gameplay[/i]
[/center]

[hr]

[size=14pt][b]What is this?[/b][/size]

[b]Computica's Faction Forks[/b] is a rehabilitation project for older Starsector faction mods, abandoned projects, and Chinese-language mods that deserve a second life.

The goal is not to erase the identity of the original mods, but to make them easier to play, easier to maintain, and easier to enjoy on modern Starsector installs.

This project focuses on:

[list]
[li][b]Restoring older faction mods[/b] that are outdated, broken, abandoned, or difficult to run.[/li]
[li][b]Translating Chinese mods into proper English[/b], with natural phrasing instead of rough machine translation.[/li]
[li][b]Code optimization and cleanup[/b] to reduce bloat, fix errors, and improve maintainability.[/li]
[li][b]Balance and polish tweaks[/b] where needed, especially when something is clearly broken, awkward, or unfinished.[/li]
[li][b]Compatibility bridging[/b] with major non-faction mods such as Ashes of The Domain, Industrial.Evolution, Nexerelin, and Star Lords.[/li]
[/list]

[hr]

[size=14pt][b]Project Philosophy[/b][/size]

These are [b]forks[/b], not hostile takeovers.

The intent is to honor the original work while making it playable, readable, and stable for the current community. Original authors, artists, translators, and contributors will be credited wherever possible.

If you are an original creator and have concerns about one of these forks, please contact me. I am willing to correct credits, adjust distribution, or remove material if needed.

[quote]
[b]Honor the past. Improve the present. Forge the future.[/b]
[/quote]

[hr]

[size=14pt][b]What I Usually Change[/b][/size]

Depending on the condition of each mod, a fork may include:

[list]
[li]Updated mod_info files[/li]
[li]Crash fixes[/li]
[li]CSV cleanup[/li]
[li]Faction, market, and ship data corrections[/li]
[li]Weapon, hullmod, and variant fixes[/li]
[li]Translation and localization improvements[/li]
[li]Balance tweaks[/li]
[li]Removal of broken, unused, or redundant code[/li]
[li]General quality-of-life improvements[/li]
[/list]

I try to avoid unnecessary redesigns unless the mod is so broken or unfinished that deeper work is needed.

[hr]

[size=14pt][b]Compatibility Bridging[/b][/size]

In addition to restoring and polishing faction mods, [b]Computica's Faction Forks[/b] also aims to improve compatibility with major non-faction mods and broader campaign-layer systems.

The goal is to help older or translated factions interact more cleanly with popular Starsector ecosystem mods instead of feeling isolated, broken, or outdated.

Current compatibility targets include:

[list]
[li][b]Ashes of The Domain[/b][/li]
[li][b]Industrial.Evolution[/b][/li]
[li][b]Nexerelin[/b][/li]
[li][b]Star Lords[/b][/li]
[/list]

Compatibility work may include:

[list]
[li]Faction integration fixes[/li]
[li]Market and industry adjustments[/li]
[li]Diplomacy and invasion behavior review[/li]
[li]Campaign-layer balance checks[/li]
[li]Economy and production compatibility passes[/li]
[li]Correcting broken or outdated mod interactions[/li]
[li]Adding support where the original mod never had it[/li]
[/list]

These bridges will vary by fork. Some factions may only need light cleanup, while others may require deeper campaign-side work to function properly alongside larger modlists.

[b]Note:[/b] Compatibility support does not mean every possible mod combination is guaranteed. The goal is practical stability, better integration, and cleaner behavior with commonly used Starsector mod setups.

[hr]

[size=14pt][b]Chinese Mod Translation Work[/b][/size]

Some of the mods handled here originate from the Chinese Starsector community. These often have interesting factions, ships, systems, and worldbuilding, but the English text can be difficult to understand or incomplete.

For those projects, I focus on:

[list]
[li]Natural English faction descriptions[/li]
[li]Readable ship, weapon, hullmod, and industry names[/li]
[li]Clear tooltips and descriptions[/li]
[li]Consistent naming conventions[/li]
[li]Preserving the original tone where possible[/li]
[/list]

This is not just “machine translation and upload.” The goal is to make the text feel like it belongs in a polished English Starsector mod.

[hr]

[size=14pt][b]Development Tools / Assistance[/b][/size]

I am also using [b]Codex[/b] as part of the workflow.

Codex helps with code review, refactoring, bug hunting, JSON/CSV cleanup, scripting assistance, and identifying possible optimization paths. Final decisions, testing priorities, balance judgment, and release direction are still handled manually.

In short:

[list]
[li][b]Human-led project[/b][/li]
[li][b]Codex-assisted cleanup and development[/b][/li]
[li][b]Community feedback welcome[/b][/li]
[/list]

